================================================================================
RECOMMENDATIONS FOR PHASE 3 (API MIGRATION)
================================================================================

Based on the database discovery findings, the following considerations should
inform Phase 3 (API Migration) planning:

1. PRIORITIZE FRANCHISE & STORE ADMIN CRUD
   These are the only fully implemented features in the FaaS application.
   Migration effort: LOW (straightforward CRUD with Express.js patterns)

2. DEFER PET & ORDER API MIGRATION
   These endpoints exist in the FaaS OpenAPI spec but have no implementation
   (authorization wrapper only). Treat as greenfield development, not migration.

3. AUTHORIZATION REFACTORING
   The AVP (Amazon Verified Permissions) integration is the core complexity.
   Options for IaaS:
   a) Maintain AVP integration (requires AWS SDK and policy store management)
   b) Implement application-level RBAC using frameworks (e.g., CASL, Casbin)
   c) Use IaaS framework guards/decorators (e.g., NestJS guards with Passport.js)
   
   Recommendation: Evaluate authorization requirements and select appropriate
   framework BEFORE starting Phase 3 backend migration.

4. DATA ACCESS LAYER ABSTRACTION
   The Lambda functions directly call DynamoDB SDK commands. The IaaS target
   should use a repository pattern or ORM (e.g., TypeORM, Prisma) to:
   - Abstract data access (enable future database switching)
   - Enforce schema validation (DTOs, entity classes)
   - Support transactions (not available in FaaS DynamoDB operations)

5. TEST DATA REQUIREMENTS
   Create realistic test data sets for:
   - Franchise entities (10-20 records)
   - Store entities (50-100 records with franchise associations)
   - Pet entities (200-500 records, NEW data)
   - Order entities (100-200 records, NEW data)
   
   Use synthetic data for Phases 1-2, migrate production Franchise/Store data
   only after validation.


================================================================================
RISKS & MITIGATION STRATEGIES
================================================================================

RISK 1: DYNAMIC SCHEMA INCONSISTENCIES
Description: Production Franchise/Store data may contain unexpected attributes
due to lack of validation in Lambda functions.
Impact: MEDIUM — Data migration scripts may fail on unexpected data shapes
Mitigation:
- Perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) on production DynamoDB snapshots
- Implement data cleaning logic in migration scripts
- Create schema validation reports before final migration

RISK 2: REFERENTIAL INTEGRITY VIOLATIONS
Description: Franchise.stores array may reference non-existent store IDs.
Store.franchise.id may reference non-existent franchise IDs.
Impact: MEDIUM — Broken relationships after data migration
Mitigation:
- Validate all foreign key references during migration
- Generate orphan record reports
- Decide on handling strategy: discard, create placeholders, or manual review

RISK 3: COGNITO INTEGRATION CHANGES
Description: IaaS implementation may change authentication system, breaking
existing user workflows.
Impact: HIGH — Existing users cannot log in
Mitigation:
- Maintain Cognito integration in IaaS MVP
- If replacing Cognito, implement user migration and credential reset workflows
- Test authorization logic with production JWT tokens

RISK 4: AVP POLICY MIGRATION
Description: Cedar policy language rules may not translate directly to
application-level RBAC.
Impact: HIGH — Authorization bypasses or false denials
Mitigation:
- Extract all Cedar policies from AVP policy store
- Create authorization test suite with all policy combinations
- Validate that IaaS authorization produces identical ALLOW/DENY results

RISK 5: MISSING BUSINESS LOGIC
Description: 50% of features (Pet, Order management) have no source implementation.
Impact: LOW for migration, HIGH for greenfield development
Mitigation:
- Acknowledge this is NEW FEATURE DEVELOPMENT, not migration
- Allocate separate project timeline and resources
- Do not conflate migration effort with greenfield effort in project planning


